{"title":"Wiki-LLaVA: Hierarchical Retrieval-Augmented Generation for Multimodal LLMs","domain":"MULTIMODAL","seeds":[{"problem":"Multimodal LLMs (e.g., LLaVA) struggle with knowledge-intensive visual questions that require information not contained in model parameters or the input image.","method":"Introduce Wiki-LLaVA, the first MLLM augmented with an external retrieval module. It performs hierarchical retrieval over a multimodal Wikipedia-like memory: (1) entity/document retrieval by matching the query image’s CLIP embedding against document title embeddings via inner-product with approximate k-NN (Faiss HNSW), returning top-k documents; (2) passage retrieval within each document using Contriever to embed question and text chunks, selecting top-n chunks by inner-product similarity. The raw retrieved passages are concatenated into the MLLM prompt alongside image tokens and the question, without changing the base architecture, reusing the same CLIP ViT-L/14@336 encoder for both vision tokens and the image query. This design substantially improves knowledge-based VQA, with further gains when oracle entities are used."},{"problem":"Fine-tuning an MLLM to use retrieved context can degrade its general multimodal capabilities across standard benchmarks.","method":"Adopt a data-mixing fine-tuning strategy using LoRA adapters: train on knowledge-based VQA pairs (Encyclopedic-VQA, InfoSeek) mixed with LLaVA-Instruct samples within each mini-batch to regularize learning. This preserves performance on general MLLM benchmarks (e.g., MME, MMMU, MMB, POPE) compared to fine-tuning solely on knowledge-based data, while enabling the model to better exploit retrieved passages when provided as additional context."}]}
